\begin_layout Subsection
Spectral resolution effects
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Aquisition of a spectrum implies that there is a minimum spectral resolution.
 The consequence of this constraint is that it limits the mininum interference
 fringe period that can be measured, and therefore, the observable range.
 Full analysis make use of 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Shannon sampling theorem"
target "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nyquist%E2%80%93Shannon_sampling_theorem"

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Formula \[
g\left(\nu_{i}\right)=\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}G\left(\nu\right)R\left(\nu-\nu_{i}\right)d\nu\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The measurement range of the FDOCT device depends on the spectral resolution
 of the spectrometer.
 Practically the useful information about the object structure is deciphered
 by the numerical Fourier transform FFT of the measured signal.
 The number of sampling points N is given by the number of illuminated CCD
 pixels.
 The dependence between the jth har- monic and the optical path difference
 j is the following
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
l_{j}=\frac{1}{2n}\frac{\lambda_{0}^{2}}{\Delta\lambda}j,\, j=1,2,\ldots,N/2\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where n is the refractive index and is the registered width of the spectrum.
 According to the Nyquist condition the index of the maximum harmonics is
 equal to N/2.
 Therefore the maximum path difference registered by a FDOCT device is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
l_{\text{max}}=\frac{1}{4\pi}\frac{\lambda_{0}^{2}}{\Delta\lambda}N.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

