 of a research.
 Time and money.
 Every fabrication step has a lead time even if cost is not .
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Diffraction Grating Spectrometers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is difficult to enumerate all the contribuition to society that diffraction
 grating has brought.
 Its role on identifying the discrete energy levels of atoms provided a
 significant amount of information to the development of quantum mechanics.
 Currently its use in the identification or quantification of chemical compounds
 and its structure constitutes the majority usage end of diffraction gratings.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Historically, diffraction grating spectrometers have been builky table top
 devices.
 But sizes have been decreasing, and handheld devices are already comercialized.
 Further in the chapter we will discuss how the devices is limited.
 Because of its role in chemical analysis this device would...
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Diffraction grating spectrometers can be integrated on chips, and this type
 of devices have been manufactured for wavelength demultiplexing devices
 in the telecomunication industry.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
alternatives
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Multiaperture planar waveguide spectrometer formed by arrayed Mach-Zehnder
 interferometers
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Florjanczyk:2007p1602"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Kirchhoff's diffraction theory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
U\left(P\right)=-\frac{iA}{2\lambda}\iint_{A}\frac{e^{ik\left(r+s\right)}}{rs}\left[\cos\left(n,r\right)-\cos\left(n,s\right)\right]dS\label{eq:Fresnel-Kirchhoff diffraction integral}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For aperture much smaller then 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 then, putting the origin somewhere in the aperture
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
U\left(P\right)\sim-\frac{Ai}{\lambda}\frac{\cos\delta}{r's'}\iint_{A}e^{ik\left(r+s\right)},\label{eq:small aperture approximation integral}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where
\begin_inset Formula \[
U\left(p,q\right)=\iint G\left(\xi,\eta\right)\exp\left[-\frac{2\pi}{\lambda}\left(p\xi+q\eta\right)\right]d\xi d\eta,\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is the pupil function.
\begin_inset Formula \[
U\left(p,q\right)=C\sum_{n}\iint_{A}e^{-ik\left[\left(\xi_{n}+\xi'\right)p+\left(\eta_{n}+\eta'\right)q\right]}d\xi'd\eta'\]

\end_inset

or
\begin_inset Formula \[
U\left(p,q\right)=C\sum_{n}e^{-ik\left(\xi_{n}p+\eta_{n}q\right)}\iint_{A}e^{-ik\left(\xi'p+\eta'q\right)}d\xi'd\eta'\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \[
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Diffraction grating
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Diffraction-grating"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
center{
\backslash
input{grating-theory.pdf_tex}}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Diffraction grating cross section.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A diffraction grating may be defined as any arrangement which imposes on
 an incident wave a periodic variation of amplitude of phase, or both.
 We may characterize any particular grating by its 
\emph on
transmission function
\emph default

\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Born:2000p1607"

\end_inset

, defined as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let a transparent or semitransparent object (not necessarily periodic) cover
 a portion of a fictitious reference plane 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi\eta$
\end_inset

, and let it be illuminated by a plane monochromatic wave incident in a
 direction specified by the direction cosines 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{0}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Fig illustrates the arrangement, the 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

-axis being perpendicular to the plane of he drawing.
 If no object were present, the disturbance in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi,\eta$
\end_inset

-plane would be represented by the function 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}\left(\xi,\eta\right)=A\exp\left[ik\left(l_{0}\xi+m_{0}\eta\right)\right]$
\end_inset

, the factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\exp\left(-i\omega t\right)$
\end_inset

 being, as usual, omitted.
 Because of the presence of the object disturbance will be modified and
 may be represented by some other function, which we denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\xi,\eta\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\emph on
transmission function
\emph default
 of the object is then defined as
\begin_inset Formula \[
F\left(\xi,\eta\right)=\frac{V\left(\xi,\eta\right)}{V_{0}\left(\xi,\eta\right)}.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In general 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 depends, not only on 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

 but also on the direction 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(l_{0},m_{0}\right)$
\end_inset

 of illumination.
 The transmission function is in general complex, since both the amplitude
 and the phase of the light may be altered on the passing through the object.
 In the special case when the object alters the amplitude but no the phase
 of the incident wave (i.e.
 if arg 
\begin_inset Formula $F\equiv0$
\end_inset

), we speak of an 
\emph on
amplitude object
\emph default
; if it alters the phase but not the amplitude (i.
 e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|F\right|=1$
\end_inset

) we speak of a 
\emph on
phase object
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we are concerned with reflected light rather than with light that is
 transmitted by an object, it is more appropriate to speak of a 
\emph on
reflection function
\emph default
, defined in a similar way, the only difference being that the reference
 plane is on the same side of the object as the incident light.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The ratio 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|V/V_{0}\right|$
\end_inset

 is practically unity for points outside the geometrical shadow (whose boundary
 is represented by points A and B in Figure) cast by the object.
 If the portion outside the shadow region is covered by an opaque screen,
 the arrangements act as a diffracting aperture A with a nonuniform pupil
 function.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
st{
\end_layout

\end_inset

If the linear dimensions of A are large compared to the wavelength and if
 F remains sensibly constant over regions whose dimensions are of the same
 order as the wavelength, the diffraction formula remain valid under the
 same conditions as before, provided that the integrand of the diffraction
 integral is multiplied by F.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename graphs/diffraction grating basic.eps

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now consider a one-dimensional grating consisting of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 parallel grooves of arbitrary profile, ruled on one surface of a plan-parallel
 glass plate.
 Let the 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi,\eta$
\end_inset

-plane coincide with the plane face of the plate, 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

 being the direction of the grooves and let 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 be the period in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

 direction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assume that the direction of propagation of the wave incident upon the grating
 is in the plane of the figure, making an angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{0}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $O\zeta$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 denote the angle which 
\begin_inset Formula $O\zeta$
\end_inset

 makes with the line joining a very distant point of observation P with
 the grating.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As before we set 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{o}=\sin\theta_{0}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $l=\sin\theta$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p=l-l_{0}=\sin\theta-\sin\theta_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 The complex amplitude at 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is then immediately obtained from, where the integrand must be multiplied
 by the transmission function 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 of one periodic element.
 We may set 
\begin_inset Formula $q=0$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula \[
\begin{array}{ccc}
\xi_{n}=nd, & \eta_{n}=0 & \left(n=0,1,\ldots,N-1\right)\end{array}.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We the obtain
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
U\left(p\right)=U^{\left(0\right)}\left(p\right)\sum_{n=0}^{N-1}e^{-ikndp}=U^{\left(0\right)}\left(p\right)\frac{1-e^{-iNkdp}}{1-e^{-kdp}},\label{eq: Up}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
U^{\left(0\right)}\left(p\right)=C\int_{A}\! F\left(\xi\right)e^{-ikp\xi}\, d\xi.\label{eq: diffraction envelope}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hence
\begin_inset Formula \[
I\left(p\right)=\left|U\left(p\right)\right|^{2}=\frac{\left(1-e^{-Nkdp}\right)}{\left(1-e^{-kdp}\right)}\cdot\frac{\left(1-e^{Nkdp}\right)}{\left(1-e^{kdp}\right)}\left|U^{\left(0\right)}\left(p\right)\right|^{2}=\frac{1-\cos Nkdp}{1-\cos kdp}I^{\left(0\right)}\left(p\right),\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $I^{\left(0\right)}\left(p\right)=\left|U^{\left(0\right)}\left(p\right)\right|^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 If we introduce the function
\begin_inset Formula \[
H\left(N,x\right)=\left(\frac{\sin Nx}{\sin x}\right)^{2},\]

\end_inset

 the formula 5 for the intensity may be written as
\begin_inset Formula \[
I\left(p\right)=H\left(N,\frac{kdp}{2}\right)I^{\left(0\right)}\left(p\right).\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Before discussing the implications of this basic formula we note that according
 to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: Up"

\end_inset

.
 The light distribution is the same as that due to a set of coherent secondary
 sources each characterized by the same amplitude function 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|U^{\left(0\right)}\left(p\right)\right|$
\end_inset

 and with phases that differ form each other by integral multiples of 
\begin_inset Formula $kdp$
\end_inset

.
 To see the significance of this phase difference consider two corresponding
 points 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 in the neighboring grooves of the grating.
 Since the effect of the grating is to impress a periodic variation onto
 the incident wave, it follows that the path difference between the light
 arriving a 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and at 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is the same as in the absence of the grating, i.e.
 it is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $AK=d\sin\theta_{0}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 denoting the foot of the perpendicular from 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 on to the ray incident at 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Further, the light path from 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 in the direction 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 exceeds the light path from 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $BL=d\sin\theta$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 being the foot of the perpendicular from 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 on to the ray diffracted at 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 in the direction 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta.$
\end_inset

 Hence the total path difference between light arriving at the distant point
 of observation form corresponding points in two neighboring grooves is
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
BL-AK=d\left(\sin\theta-\sin\theta_{0}\right)=dp,\label{eq: path difference}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 and the corresponding phase difference is 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi dp/\lambda=kdp$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Formula expresses 
\begin_inset Formula $I\left(p\right)$
\end_inset

 as the product of two functions: one of them, 
\begin_inset Formula $I^{\left(0\right)}$
\end_inset

, represents the effect of a single period of the grating; the other, 
\begin_inset Formula $H\left(N,x\right)$
\end_inset

 has maxima, each of height 
\begin_inset Formula $N^{2}$
\end_inset

 when
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
p\equiv\sin\theta-\sin\theta_{0}=\frac{m\lambda}{Nd}\left(m=0,\pm1,\pm2,\ldots\right),\label{eq:grating equation}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The integer 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 represents, according to 7, the path difference in wavelengths between
 light diffracted in the direction of the maximum, from corresponding points
 in two neighboring grooves.
 In agreement with our earlier definition,7.3.1, we call 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 the 
\emph on
order of interference
\emph default
.
 Between theses principal maxima there are weak secondary maxima (see fig
 8.19a), the first secondary maximum being only a few percent of the principal
 maximum when 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is large.
 The maxima are separated by points of zero intensity at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=kdp/2=\pm n\pi/N$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 in directions given by
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
p\equiv\sin\theta-\sin\theta_{0}=\frac{n\lambda}{Nd}\left(n=0,\pm1,\pm2,\ldots\right)\label{eq: grating secondary maxima}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
the case where 
\begin_inset Formula $n/N$
\end_inset

 is an integer being excluded.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The function 
\begin_inset Formula $I^{\left(0\right)}\left(p\right)$
\end_inset

 depends on the form of the grooves.
 Suppose that it has principal maximum for some direction 
\begin_inset Formula $p=p'$
\end_inset

 and that on both sides of the maximum if falls off slowly in comparison
 with 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $I\left(p\right)$
\end_inset

 will have the general form o the sharp maxima near the directions 
\begin_inset Formula $p=m\lambda/d$
\end_inset

.
 Since these directions (except for 
\begin_inset Formula $m=0$
\end_inset

) depend on the wavelength, we see that the grating will decompose a beam
 of non-monochromatic light into 
\emph on
spectral orders
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To illustrate these remarks let us consider a grating consisting of a succession
 of long equidistant slits, each of width 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 and length 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

, in an opaque screen.
 If the grating is illuminated from a very distant line source parallel
 to the slits, the intensity 
\begin_inset Formula $I^{\left(0\right)}$
\end_inset

 is given by the expression 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: diffraction envelope"

\end_inset

 (with 
\begin_inset Formula $2a=s$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $2b=L$
\end_inset

) and we obtain
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
I\left(p\right)=\frac{sE}{\lambda R^{2}}\left(\frac{\sin\frac{Nkdp}{2}}{\sin\frac{kdp}{2}}\right)^{2}\left(\frac{\sin\frac{kdp}{2}}{\frac{kdp}{2}}\right)^{2}.\label{eq: diffraction intensity}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Curves representing the two factors in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: diffraction intensity"

\end_inset

 and their product are shown in fig X.
 The last factor in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: diffraction intensity"

\end_inset

, which represents the effect of a single slit, has a principal maximum
 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p=0$
\end_inset

 and minima given by 
\begin_inset Formula $ksp/2=n\pi$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 at
\begin_inset Formula \[
p=\frac{n\lambda}{s},\left(n=0,\pm1,\pm2,\ldots\right)\]

\end_inset

 separated by weak secondary maxima.
 We see that if 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda/s\gg\lambda/d$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 if the width of each slit is small compared to 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

, the intensity 
\begin_inset Formula $I\left(p\right)$
\end_inset

 has in addition to a principal maximum at 
\begin_inset Formula $p=0$
\end_inset

 a series of sharp, but progressively decreasing, maxima on either side
 of it, near direction given by 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:grating equation"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Returning to the general case, it is evident that if the width of each groove
 is very small, of the order of a wavelength (as is often the case in practice)
 the formula derived on the basis of Kirchhoff's approximation, can evidently
 no longer be expected to hold.
 In such cases more refined considerations must be make to determine the
 detailed distribution of the intensity.
 We may, however, expect that the main qualitative features indicated by
 our elementary theory, namely the existence of sharp maxima whose positions
 are substantially determined by the interference function 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

, remain even when the grooves are very narrow, provided, that the intensity
 function of a single period varies slowly in an interval of the order 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta p=\lambda/d$
\end_inset

.
 Let us now consider the resolution that may be attained with a grating.
 The separation between a primary maximum of order 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 and a neighbouring minimum is, according to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: grating secondary maxima"

\end_inset

, given by
\begin_inset Formula \[
\Delta p=\frac{\lambda}{Nd}.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the wavelength is changed by an amount 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\lambda$
\end_inset

, the 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

th-order maximum is according to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:grating equation"

\end_inset

, displaced by an amount
\begin_inset Formula \[
\Delta'p=\frac{\left|m\right|}{d}\Delta\lambda.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assuming that the lines of wavelength 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\pm\frac{1}{2}\Delta\lambda$
\end_inset

 will just be resolved when the maximum of the one wavelength coincides
 with the first minimum of the other we have on he limit of resolution in
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

th order, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta p=\Delta'p$
\end_inset

, i.e.
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\frac{\lambda}{\Delta\lambda}=\left|m\right|N.\label{eq: resolving power}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus, 
\emph on
the resolving power is equal to the product of the order number m and the
 number N of the grooves
\emph default
.
 For the 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

th order we have, according to, that 
\begin_inset Formula $d\left(\sin\theta-\sin\theta_{0}\right)=m\lambda$
\end_inset

, so that we may also express the resolving power in the form
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{\lambda}{\Delta\lambda}=\frac{Nd\left|\sin\theta-\sin\theta_{0}\right|}{\lambda}.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: path difference"

\end_inset

 this implies that 
\emph on
the resolving power is equal to the number of wavelengths in the path difference
 between rays that are diffracted in the direction 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 from the two extreme ends (separated by distance Nd) of the grating
\emph default
.
 It is to be noted that since 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\sin\theta-\sin\theta_{0}\right|$
\end_inset

 cannot exceed 2, the resolving power that can be attained with a grating
 of overall with 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 can never exceed the value 
\begin_inset Formula $2w/\lambda$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Free spectral range
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From the resolving power equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: resolving power"

\end_inset

, we conclude that spectrometer should be operated on high diffraction order
 so as to minimize the device size for a given resolution.
 Unfortunatelly, the grating equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:grating equation"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p\equiv\sin\theta-\sin\theta_{0}=\frac{m\lambda}{Nd}$
\end_inset

, we see that it is possible for light from to different wavelength in different
e diffraction orders to be diffracted to the same angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

, sufficing that 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
m_{i}\lambda_{i}=m_{j}\lambda_{j}\]

\end_inset

for 
\begin_inset Formula $i\neq j$
\end_inset

, so for example light diffracted in order 1 at wavelength 1500 nm is diffracted
 in the same direction as light diffracted from order 2 wavelength 750 nm.
 To avoid this ambiguity, it is of interest to know when this condition
 happens.
 From the grating equation we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 does not make sense outside the interval [0,1], therefore, 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $0\le\frac{m\lambda_{m}}{Nd}\le1$
\end_inset

 we then that for the diffraction order 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 the wavelength range that is going to be diffracted is:
\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\noun default
\color inherit
 
\begin_inset Formula \[
0\le\lambda_{m}\le\frac{Nd}{m}.\]

\end_inset

So for the first order the wavelength range that exists is every wavelength
 below 
\begin_inset Formula $Nd$
\end_inset

 , for order 2 every wavelength below 
\begin_inset Formula $Nd/2$
\end_inset

 and so on.
 We see then, that for order 1 the range 
\begin_inset Formula $[Nd,Nd/2]$
\end_inset

 is occupied solely by order one.
 For order 2 the range 
\begin_inset Formula $[Nd/2,Nd/3]$
\end_inset

, for order 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $[Nd/m,Nd/(m+1)]$
\end_inset

.
 We see that the range width 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\lambda_{m}$
\end_inset


\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\noun default
\color inherit
 which there is no overlaping diffraction, called 
\emph on
free spectral range
\emph default
, can be computed as 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\Delta\lambda_{m}=\frac{Nd}{m}-\frac{Nd}{m+1}=\frac{Nd}{m(m+1)},\]

\end_inset

we can replace the substitute the dependancy on 
\begin_inset Formula $Nd$
\end_inset

 for the wavelength in the center of the free spectral range 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{Cm}$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
\lambda_{Cm}=\frac{Nd}{m}-\frac{\Delta\lambda_{m}}{2}=\frac{Nd}{m(m+1)}(m+0.5),\]

\end_inset

It is worth noting that althought 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{Cm}$
\end_inset

 is in the middle of the spectral range 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\lambda_{m}$
\end_inset

 the wavelenths are not linearly distributed along the angle range that
 it is diffracted to, and therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{Cm}$
\end_inset

 is not located at the center of the angle range of the 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

th order free spectral range.
 [Graph]We see then that the free spectral range depends inverselly with
 the diffraction order used, 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\Delta\lambda_{m}=\frac{\lambda_{Cm}}{m+0.5}.\label{eq:FSR}\end{equation}

\end_inset

This fact, ties to use the a maximum operating diffraction order to the
 wavelength range and central wavelength we want the diffraction grating
 to operate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Planar devices
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The previous exposition on diffraction grating does not change on the medium
 in which the device is built on.
 But since we are interested in spectrometeres integrated on chips, it worth
 lifting the characteristics of this device.
 From this point two features stand out as very different from regular free
 space spectrometer.
 First is that light is always guided in a slab waveguide, the confinement
 of light in one dimension change the nature of the system from a 3 dimensional
 to bi-dimensional one.
 As this fact causes the light power to decay with the inverse of the distance
 as it moves away from the source.
 The other diference is the change of the dispersion due to both the material
 and the confinement effect.
 The outcome of this is that for all the results in the previous section,
 the wavelength variable that needs to be considered is the effective wavelenght
 in the medium.
\begin_inset Formula \[
\lambda_{\text{eff}}=\frac{\lambda}{n_{\text{eff}}}\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Spectrometer Architectures
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Several architecture to build diffraction grating spectrometer exists.
 Due to lowest size resolution of the Rowland design, it was chosen to build
 the spectrometer.
 The Czerny-Turner is presented here to introduce spectrometer because its
 design is easily understandable.
 Arrayed waveguide grating has been the most used planar (on chip) version
 of spectrometer.
 Marketed as wavelength de-multiplexer (WDM) this layout is show because
 its role in the telecommunication industry it is of interest to understand
 why it is not fit for role high resolution on chip spectrometer.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Czerny-Turner
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Czerny-Turner"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Due to its modularity this architecture is probably the best to introduce
 spectrometers.
 It is composed of two slits, two concave mirrors and a diffraction grating.
 As shown in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Czerny-Turner-architecture"

\end_inset

, the light to be analyzed is shined through the entrance slit.
 Due to diffraction, the light fan out as it propagates to the collimating
 concave mirror where light is collimated and reflected in the direction
 of the diffraction grating.
 The diffraction grating then, deviates light from each different wavelength
 (optical frequencies) into different angles following the equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:grating equation"

\end_inset

.
 A focusing concave mirror focus the light coming from the diffraction grating
 and deflect it to the detector slit.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement h
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
center{
\backslash
input{czerny-turner.pdf_tex}}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Czerny-Turner 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Czerny-Turner-architecture"

\end_inset

architecture
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The function of the entrance slit is to filter spatial optical modes that
 are inputed into the system.
 For best filtering the slit has to transmit only a single spatial mode.
 This is achieved by making the slit width of the order of the light wavelength.
 Decreasing slit width will increase the beam spread angle, as depicted
 in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:different slits"

\end_inset

, for a chosen final beam width this will allow the collimating concave
 mirror to placed nearer to the slit decreasing the device size.
 However, decrease the slit width will also decrease the fraction of transmitted
 light.
 and therefore, lowering the device sensitivity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement h
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
center{
\backslash
input{slit_width.pdf_tex}}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Different effects of slit width
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:different slits"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As described by its name the collimating concave mirror collimates the light
 coming from the entrance mirror and redirect it to the diffraction grating.
 In order to 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "collimate"
target "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Collimated_light"

\end_inset

 the input light, the curvature radius should be equal twice the distance
 from the entrance slit to the center of the collimating concave mirror.
 The mirror diameter must be bigger than the beam width at the when it arrives
 at it to avoid losing light power.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The diffraction grating deviates light from each different wavelength into
 different angles, as described by equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:grating equation"

\end_inset

.
 Details on how the light is diffracted are explained in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Diffraction-grating"

\end_inset

.
 Roughly, the number of illuminated grooves, which is equal to the beam
 diameter divided by the groove pitch, will determine the resolving power
 of the spectrometer, as shown in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: resolving power"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To quantify the amount of light deviated to each different direction, we
 use a focusing concave mirror, which will map light with different direction
 and focus them each into a distinct point in a plane.
 Alternatively we can say that light in different k in the k space into
 different points in the coordinate space.
 Clearly, the size of the focusing mirror must be such that it collects
 most of the light coming from the diffraction grating.
 This means that it must be bigger than the beam size plus account for the
 spread of different wavelengths.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A detector is placed at a point in the focus plan to measure the light power.
 Optimum detector size is of the order of the entrance slit width, limited
 also by the resolving power of the diffraction grating.
 Placing a exit slit in the focus plane followed by a detector, can be used
 as an alternative for the slit size detector.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement h
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Detector array and slit and detector options
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Size analise
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Rowland
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Rowland"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In year, Rowland 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Rowland:1883p38"

\end_inset

 found a way to incorporate the collimating and focusing elements into the
 diffraction grating.
 This layout not only decreased the final device size, but also eliminate
 spherical and astigmatism aberrations due to the auxiliary concave mirrors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The design consists in the use of a concave diffraction grating of radius
 2R.
 The entrance and exit slits positions are located in a circle of radius
 R tangent to the diffraction grating sphere.
 Or more precisely tangent to one of the equator of the diffraction grating
 sphere.
 For optimum area usage, the equator should be perpendicular to the diffraction
 grating grooves and passing through the grating center.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
center{
\backslash
input{rowland-mounting.pdf_tex}}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Rowland design.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Arrayed Waveguide Grating (AWG)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The resolving power of a diffraction grating is proportional to the number
 of grooves and diffraction order, as shown in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: resolving power"

\end_inset

.
 Diffraction grating based on ruled surfaces can not achieve diffraction
 order greater than 20.
 Introduced by Takahashi et.
 al.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Takahashi:1990p122"

\end_inset

, this limitation can be overcome by replacing the grating grooves by an
 array of waveguides.
 To understand how the introduction of waveguide help it is necessary to
 understand more generally what diffraction order is.
 We say that certain diffraction peak is of order 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 if each wave from the set that was constructively interfered to form the
 interference peak is delayed from one another of 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 periods.
 On traditional ruled surface diffraction gratings, wavefront from different
 period are made to interfere by making the wave travel different path lengths
 by taking path that deviates from the equal angle reflection.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement h
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
center{
\backslash
input{awg.pdf_tex}}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Traditional diffraction grating generate different path length by straying
 away from equal angle reflection.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By guiding light through waveguide it is possible to increase the difference
 of path length among different waveguides, achieved by only changing the
 waveguides lengths.
 Each waveguide of the waveguide array would function like a groove in the
 diffraction grating, but since waveguide length is only limited by its
 intrinsic loss, the difference of path length can be on the order of hundreds
 of wavelength, giving raise to grating that operate of diffraction order
 of also hundreds.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Unfortunately there is a drawback of increasing diffraction order, the free
 spectral range as described in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:FSR"

\end_inset

, decreases with the inverse of the of the diffraction order.
 For instance, an arrayed waveguide grating working on diffraction order
 100 at wavelength 1500 nm would have a FSR of only 15 nm.
 Although this range is useful for fiber optics telecommunications, this
 bandwidth is too small for most spectroscopy application, optical coherence
 tomography or ultra-fast oscilloscope[refs].
 Since we want to achieve a wide spectrum range, this architecture is not
 fit for us.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Grating illuminated by a Gaussian Beam
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Grating gaussian beam"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
center{
\backslash
input{gaussian-beam.pdf_tex}}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:square-gaussian"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Diffraction-grating"

\end_inset

, it was assumed that the whole grating was uniformly illuminated.
 In practice, this case not always occurs.
 Light source is normally a collimated light from a slit, pin hole or fiber
 optics, where for best resolution, single mode output should pass through.
 In those cases the tranversal power profile is better modeled by a gaussian
 than by a square profile, see figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:square-gaussian"

\end_inset

.
 To ajust the resolving power equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: resolving power"

\end_inset

 to account for the Gaussian profile illumination we have to alter the squared
 illumination assumption in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: Up"

\end_inset

.
 Using the relation we can equate 
\begin_inset Formula \[
U\left(p\right)=U^{\left(0\right)}\left(p\right)\int\sum_{n=-\infty}^{\infty}\delta\left(x-n\right)\text{rect}\left[\frac{x}{2\left(N-1\right)}\right]e^{-ikxdp}dx\]

\end_inset

where
\begin_inset Formula \[
\text{rect}\left(x\right)=\begin{cases}
0 & \mbox{if }\left|x\right|>\frac{1}{2}\\
\frac{1}{2} & \mbox{if }\left|x\right|=\frac{1}{2}\\
1 & \mbox{if }\left|x\right|<\frac{1}{2}.\end{cases}\]

\end_inset

the rect
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 function correspond to the squared illumination assumption, for a Gaussian
 illumination we simply replace tha function by a Gaussian function
\begin_inset Formula \[
\text{gauss}\mbox{\left(x\right)}=\exp\left[-4\ln2\left(\frac{x}{w/d}\right)^{2}\right]\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 is the grating pitch, and 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 is the Full Width at Half Maximum field amplitude of the illuminating beam
 at the grating.
 Replacing the Dirac delta comb by its Fourier series 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\sum_{k=-\infty}^{\infty}\delta\left(x-k\right)=\sum_{m=-\infty}^{\infty}e^{i2\pi mx},\]

\end_inset

we get
\begin_inset Formula \[
U\left(p\right)=U^{\left(0\right)}\left(p\right)\sum_{m=-\infty}^{\infty}\int\exp\left[-4\ln2\left(\frac{x}{w/d}\right)^{2}\right]e^{-i2\pi x\left(kdp/2\pi-m\right)}dx\]

\end_inset

performing the integral we obtain a comb of Gaussian 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
U\left(p\right)=U^{\left(0\right)}\left(p\right)\frac{w}{\sqrt{2}}\sum_{m=-\infty}^{\infty}\exp\left[-\frac{1}{4}\left(\frac{kdp}{2\pi}-m\right)^{2}\frac{\left(w/d\right)^{2}}{4\ln2}\right],\label{eq:gaussian comb}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where each Gaussian is centered on the diffraction order 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

.
 From it we get
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\frac{kdp}{2\pi}=m\mbox{ or }p=\frac{\lambda m}{d}.\label{eq:grating equation 2}\end{equation}

\end_inset

From equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:gaussian comb"

\end_inset

 we can define the wavelength width 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\lambda$
\end_inset

 such that the power of wavelength 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 at diffraction order 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

, is halven as a been
\begin_inset Formula \[
\Delta p=2\ln2\frac{\lambda}{w},\]

\end_inset

or using the grating equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:grating equation 2"

\end_inset

 e define the resolving power for a gaussian beam illuminated diffraction
 grating as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\frac{\lambda}{\Delta\lambda}=4\sqrt{2}\ln2\frac{wm}{d}\label{eq:resolving power gaussian}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is worth noting that the relationship between the electric field amplitude
 FWHM 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 at the grating and the power FWHM 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula \[
W=\frac{w}{\sqrt{2}}\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{\lambda}{\Delta\lambda}=8\ln2\frac{Wm}{d}\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Size
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a given wavelength 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

, resolution 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\lambda$
\end_inset

 and free spectral range 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\lambda$
\end_inset

, one would like to minimize the device size.
 Since the device size is basically defined by the grating size 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

.
 We have 
\begin_inset Formula $W=a\frac{\lambda^{2}}{\Delta\lambda}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $Nm=\frac{\lambda}{\Delta\lambda}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $W=a\frac{\lambda m}{\Delta\lambda}d$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\lambda=\frac{\lambda}{m}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $W=a\frac{\lambda^{2}}{\delta\lambda\Delta\lambda}d$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $ $
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Spectral defects
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Rowland Ghosts
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rowland ghosts are spurious lines seen in some grating spectra that result
 from periodic errors in the spacing of the grooves.
 These are usually located symmetrically with respect to each strong spectral
 line at a spectral distance from it, which depends on the period of the
 error, and with an intensity that depends on the amplitude of this error.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Lyman Ghosts
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Aberrations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The resolving power equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: resolving power"

\end_inset

 states that the resolution of a diffraction grating depends linearly with
 the wavelength.
 Unfortunatelly, that relation is only valid for plane waves.
 To use segregation capability of the diffraction grating, it is necessary
 to have a source of plane waves and to measure the light power that go
 to different direction after diffraction from the grating.
 Sources and detector are space localized endpoints.
 But employing lenses, it is possible to convert a space localized mode
 to a angle localized mode., as discussed on the Czerny-Turner configuration
 in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Czerny-Turner"

\end_inset

.
 This conversion, however, is not perfect.
 In geometrical optics terms, this means that rays that enter parallel in
 a lens (or any other focusin device) does no converge to a single point
 after the lens and with the fase arriving at exaclty the same time(picture?).
 Integrating the lens into the grating, as done in Rowland configuration
 in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Rowland"

\end_inset

, does not readily eliminate the problem, but its application together with
 the potencial to fabricate designs with freedom to choose any geometry
 and dispersion might be the solution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First we will state formally what conditions need to be satified in the
 design of a aberration free spectrometer.
 The non-existance of a mathematical solution, lead us to show two corrections,
 named one point and two point stigmatic correction, that reduce aberrations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Aberration free conditions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One would like to design a perfect spectrometer free of aberration.
 The ability of electron beam lithography to define with accuracy of nanometers
 the position and shape of the grating grooves.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
center{
\backslash
input{aberration-free.pdf_tex}}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:aberration free"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The problem can be stated as follows: Light coming from a point 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 fan out to a diffraction grating which the i-th groove, of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 grooves, is located at 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{i}$
\end_inset

, at each groove light is reflected, fans out again and propagates to a
 set of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 output waveguides which the j-ith waveguide is located at 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{j}$
\end_inset

, as shown in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:aberration free"

\end_inset

.
 To perfectly separate light from different wavelengths, we would like that
 all light which has wavelength 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{j}$
\end_inset

 coming from each groove arrive in phase at the output point 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 Furthermore, we would like that light coming from each different groove
 have be in a different cycle.
 The previeous conditions can be expressed by a system of 
\begin_inset Formula $N\times M$
\end_inset

 nonlinear algebraic equations with the prototype
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\overline{IG_{i}}+\overline{G_{i}O_{j}}=\lambda_{j}\left(a_{j}+mi\right)\text{ for }\left(i=1,2,\dots,N\right)\text{ and }\left(j=1,2,\dots,M\right),\label{eq:spectrometer equation}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is an integer number which defines the diffraction order and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{j}$
\end_inset

 is a constant that states that the absolute path length does not matter,
 only the path length difference between light coming from different routes
 do.
 It is worth emphasizing that the path length evaluation should consider
 the medium refractive index, from this perspective one can interpret that
 light is also propagating in a non-euclidean space.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the case of a flat space in a plane, equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:spectrometer equation"

\end_inset

 can be expanded to
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\sqrt{\left(I_{x}-G_{ix}\right)^{2}+\left(I_{y}-G_{iy}\right)^{2}}+\sqrt{\left(O_{jx}-G_{ix}\right)^{2}+\left(O_{jy}-G_{iy}\right)^{2}}=\lambda_{j}\left(a_{j}+mi\right)\text{ for }\left(i=1,2,\dots,N\right)\text{ and }\left(j=1,2,\dots,M\right),\label{eq:spectrometer equation expanded}\end{equation}

\end_inset

As discussed in sections 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Diffraction-grating"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Grating gaussian beam"

\end_inset

, high resolution implies in the use of a high number of grooves 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

  with numbers tipically achieving, thousands to millions.
 Number of channels 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is, of course, as a wish of the costumer but numbers around thousands are
 very typical.
 These implies that the set of equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:spectrometer equation expanded"

\end_inset

 is comprised of 
\begin_inset Formula $M\times N$
\end_inset

 equations with and 
\begin_inset Formula $2N+2C+1$
\end_inset

 variables 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All equation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
show that there is no build the full set of equations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
cite the papers that show it is not possible to solve for Euclidean surface
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Marz:1992p28,Beutler:1945p8,Namioka:1959p48,Velzel:1976p67"

\end_inset

, but nothing has been shown for non-Euclidean surfaces.
 Fabrication of non-Euclidean surfaces have been used to demonstrate cloaking
 devices
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Gabrielli:2009p1173"

\end_inset

.
 Although it is not possible to find a solution for all equations, solving
 for one and two points dramatically improves aberration.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
One point stigmatic correction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the modality a degree of freedom is left undefined leaving us the possibility
 to choose the surface in which the diffraction grooves are going to be
 positioned
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "McGreer:1996p15"

\end_inset

.
 Using the Rowland design as a basis, we show here how to place the grooves
 on a circle in order to have a wavelength free of aberration.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename graphs/aberrationComp.eps

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Two points stigmatic correction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Horst:2009p1764,Gidon:1988p1765"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Blazing and Groove size
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Rayleigh-Huygens model
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Rayleigh-Huygens-model"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Numerical calculation where carried out using a Rayleigh-Huygens method
 adapted to a bidimensional world
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Brouckaert:2007p82"

\end_inset

.
 The implementation was done in a Python script program.
 And the program is available at 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "http://code.google.com/p/khsimulator/"
target "http://code.google.com/p/khsimulator/"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
\align center
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
input{KH.pdf_tex}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
\align center
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
According to the Kirchhoff-Huygens diffraction formula, the incident electric
 field 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{\text{inc}}$
\end_inset

 at the center points of the grating facets 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(P'\right)$
\end_inset

 at a distance 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1}$
\end_inset

and at an angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{s}$
\end_inset

 can be calculated as 
\begin_inset Formula \[
E_{\text{inc}}=\frac{1}{2}\sqrt{\frac{n_{\text{eff}}}{\lambda}}\int E_{\text{wg}}\left(y\right)\frac{e^{-jkr_{1}}}{\sqrt{r_{1}}}\left(1-\cos\alpha_{s}\right)dy\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $k=2\pi n_{\text{eff}}/\lambda$
\end_inset

 is the wavenumber within the slab waveguide, and 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{\text{wg}}$
\end_inset

 is the electric field profile of the TE-polarized fundamental mode of the
 input waveguide.
 Similarly, the diffracted field 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{\text{out}}$
\end_inset

 on the collection wavguides is calculated as 
\begin_inset Formula \[
E_{\text{out}}\left(P''\right)=\eta\sqrt{\frac{n_{\text{eff}}}{\lambda}}\sum_{\text{Grating}}\int_{-D/2}^{+D/2}E_{\text{inc}}\left(y\right)\frac{e^{-jkr_{2}}}{\sqrt{r_{2}}}\frac{\left(\cos\alpha_{i}-\cos\alpha_{d}\right)}{2}dy'\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{d}$
\end_inset

 are the incident and diffracted angles with respect to the normal of each
 grating facet, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

 is the reflection coefficient of the grating.
 This formula is simplified if we assume that the magnitude of the incident
 field 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|E_{\text{inc}}\right|$
\end_inset

is constant over each facet and the pahse of this field changes linearly
 along the length of the facet
\begin_inset Formula \[
E_{\text{inc}}\left(y'\right)=E_{\text{inc}}\left(y'=0\right)e^{+iky'\sin\alpha_{i}}.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This aaproximation is valid if the sie of the facets is small compared with
 the distance to the input and if thangle of incidence 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{i}$
\end_inset

 is small.
 This is thye case if the blaze point 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(O\right)$
\end_inset

 is positioned near the input waveguide 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(I\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Comparisons of simulationas and analitic solution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Simulation of Spectral defects and aberrations using Rayleigh-Huygens model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
implementation
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:implementation"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Chowdhury:2000p56"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The integration of silicon photonics and electronics in a CMOS compatible
 platform enables whole monolithic device such as a wavelength division
 demultiplexer (WDM) integrated with detectors and electronic amplifiers.
 Most silicon-on-insulator (SOI) WDMs with 1 nm channel spacing typically
 cover a spectral range of only 10 nm.
 The small spectral range in typical WDMs is due to the use of arrayed waveguide
 grating (AWG)
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Nitkowski:2008p58,Ellis:2006p27"

\end_inset

 designs where large grating orders are employed to achieve small channel
 spacing which comes with the cost of free spectral range.
 It is possible to increase the spectral range by lowering the grating order
 and adding more waveguides to compensate, but this increases the overall
 chip size.
 Furthermore, due to the high index contrast of the silicon photonics platform,
 the achievable resolution depends on very fine control of the AWG waveguide
 dimensions.
 Here we demonstrate WDM using etched diffraction grating (EDG)
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Kneipp:1999p20,MahadevanJansen:2010p89,Foster:2008p71"

\end_inset

.
 This design is more fabrication tolerant since light is propagating in
 a slab where the only dimension that needs to be controlled is the slab
 thickness.
 It is also more suitable to work at a low grating order because light diffracts
 in a single slab opposed to the two star couplers slabs in the AWG.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Design
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We designed a WDM that uses a Rowland design with one stigmatic point correction.
 The system was designed so that stigmatic point was located at the central
 waveguide of the 21 output waveguide array.
 The central wavelength was chosen to be 1500 nm and the diffraction order
 was 10.
 The Rowland circle was chosen to be 750 μm.
 The designed grating contains 340 grooves.
 The resulting free spectral range was estimated to be 117 nm, and the groove
 spacing approximately 4 μm.
 The input and output waveguide apertures were 1.4 μm.
 A reference waveguide was placed next to the spectrometer so that the transmiss
ion efficiency could be estimated.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Operating wavelength
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Due to the readly avaibility of testing equipment operating at 1460-1610
 nm range we decided to design the system to operate somewhere at this range.
 Germanium detector have a peak detection at 1500 nm so we decided to design
 the spectrometer operating range centered at 1500 nm.
\end_layout

