\begin_layout Subsection
Grating size
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The spectrometer was patterned using a 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "JEOL 9300FS"
target "http://www.cnfusers.cornell.edu/cnf5_tool.taf?_function=detail&eq_id=33&gtitle=ELECTRON-BEAM%20LITHOGRAPHY&area=ELECTRON-BEAM%20LITHOGRAPHY&cacName=JEOL%209300&labUser=1&_UserReference=2652A565A61BF5B34CC5BA72"

\end_inset

 electron beam lithographer.
 The system is capable of writing using only beam deflecton on an area (denomina
ted 
\emph on
field size
\emph default
) of 1x1 mm.
 By moving the sample to be written (process called as 
\emph on
stitching
\emph default
) one is capable of writing a whole 5x5 inches mask.
 Unfortunatelly due to the extreme precision required, it is difficult to
 align the boders of neighboring fields perfectly, with the system working
 its best alignments of 10 nm are possible, though achieving this kind of
 precision is requires a good amount of trials and experience, alignments
 of 50 nm are more routinelly achieved.
 In order to avoid errors in the spectrometer grating during stitching we
 limited the size of the grating in order of it to fit in a single 1x1 mm
 field, which meant placing the grating along the diagonal of the field,
 which, ignoring the grating curvature, gaves us a grating size of 1.4 mm.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Diffraction order and input, output angles
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As stated on section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:resolving power gaussian"

\end_inset

 a higher resolving power can be achieved due to arguments to be described
 at X we limited our operating range to 150 nm, this would allow us to operate
 at diffraction order -10 or 10.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
According to the grating equation 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Number of grooves
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The higher the number of grooves the higher resolving power we can get.
 But since we want to limit the grating size, in this particular device
 to 1.4 mm.
 Increasing the number of grooves also means decreaing pitch size and increase
 of diffraction angle, as shown in graph X.
 
\end_layout

