\end_inset

angular dispersion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{\partial\theta_{\text{out}}}{\partial\lambda}=\frac{m}{a\left[1+\left(m\frac{\lambda}{a}+\sin\theta_{\text{in}}\right)^{2}\right]}\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We design the DG spectrometer using the Rowland architecture.
 To reduce spherical aberration, a non-uniform groove spacing is employed
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "McGreer:1996p15"

\end_inset

.
 Metal heaters are added above the silicon layer 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "SherwoodDroz:2008p57"

\end_inset

 to align the resonator and spectrometer transmission combs using the thermo-opt
ic effect in silicon.
 The diffraction grating spectrometer contains 25 channels with spacing
 of 1 nm.
 To match the ring resonator FSR to the DG spectrometer channel spacing
 we use an 83.5 m radius ring with waveguide cross-section of 450 x 250 nm.
 The FSR changes with wavelength according to 
\begin_inset Formula $2\lambda/(n_{g}L)$
\end_inset

, but considering a slight positive group velocity dispersion (
\begin_inset Formula $\partial n_{g}/\partial\lambda\approx3.6\times10^{-3}\text{nm}^{-1}$
\end_inset

) this change is extremely small: the total change in FSR across the range
 of operation (25 nm) is approximately 1% for light polarized in the plane
 of the device (TE polarization).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Output posistioning
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Output waveguide positioning
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For better accuracy on spectrometer channels output wavelengths.
 Each channel was positioned not accordingly to equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:grating equation"

\end_inset

 but by maximizing the output transmission depending on the output waveguide
 position, where the transmission was calculated numerically.
 Deviation from the grating equation result are attributed to the non-uniformity
 of grating grooves distribuition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Fabrication
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We fabricated the device using CMOS compatible procedures.
 First, we start with an SOI wafer with 250 nm silicon and 3 μm buried oxide.
 An 80 nm layer of SiO2 was deposited using plasma enhanced chemical vapor
 deposition (PECVD) to be used as a hard mask.
 A 200 nm layer of PMMA was spun and then the grating and the waveguides
 were defined using e-beam lithography.
 The pattern was transferred from PMMA the to the oxide layer using CHF3/O2
 reactive ion etch.
 The silicon layer was etched using Cl2 inductively coupled plasmaand then
 2.3 μm of SiO2 was deposited using PECVD to clad the device.
 The wafer was diced and polished for optical testing.
\end_layout

